  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "An entry method using the highest and lowest candle bodies of a consolidation range as box boundaries. Price aggressively deviates (manipulates) beyond the box, then rapidly returns inside. Entry is taken on the retest of the deviation zone, with a stop beyond the manipulation extreme. Targets are set at the opposite side of the range or using standard deviation projections of the manipulation leg, often aligning with liquidity pools or structural levels.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a consolidation range where price fails to make new highs/lows; mark the box boundaries using the highest and lowest candle bodies (not wicks), except on daily charts where wicks are acceptable.",
    "Wait for an aggressive deviation move outside the box that sweeps liquidity (e.g., old high/low) and then aggressively returns back inside, forming a wick on a higher time frame.",
    "Confirm the manipulation with a change in state of delivery (close back through the opposing candle series) or a decisive close inside the range.",
    "Mark the deviation zone (area between the range extreme and the deviation high/low) as the area of interest for retest.",
    "Enter on the retest of the box boundary (the deviation zone) after price returns inside; place stop loss just beyond the manipulation high (for shorts) or low (for longs).",
    "If the direct retest is unclear, wait for an order block or a close-through candle inside the deviation zone to validate entry, with stop on the order block extreme.",
    "Set profit targets at the opposite side of the range or using standard deviation projections of the manipulation leg (levels like -1, -2 to -2.5, -4), aligning with fair value gaps or prior swing points.",
    "Use higher time frames (1H, 4H, daily) for bias and lower time frames (15M, 5M, 30s) for execution.",
    "Confirm price is in discount (for longs) or premium (for shorts) before entry.",
    "If the consolidation is unclear, identify the aggressive displacement first, then look left to find the box boundaries."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The Box Setup operationalizes the AMD cycle, capturing early entries after a liquidity sweep without waiting for a full market structure shift. It provides a defined entry on the retest of the range boundary after manipulation, with a tight stop beyond the manipulation extreme, targeting opposite-side liquidity or standard deviation projections, often achieving at least 2R. Confluence from FVGs, order blocks, or CISD enhances entry quality. Effective across multiple time frames for both bias and refined entries.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Marking the box using wicks instead of candle bodies on intraday time frames (daily charts are an exception).",
    "Entering on the initial deviation without waiting for the aggressive return into the range and retest of the box boundary.",
    "Taking the setup when the out-and-back move is not aggressive, resulting in an invalid wick formation.",
    "Placing the stop loss too tight or not beyond the manipulation high/low, leading to premature stop-outs.",
    "Failing to confirm displacement with a decisive close outside/inside the box and a change in state of delivery before entry.",
    "Setting profit targets without correctly projecting standard deviation levels from the manipulation leg's swing high/low anchor.",
    "Ignoring confluence with higher time frame bias, PD arrays, or other structural factors.",
    "Confusing the Box Setup with a Balanced Price Range (BPR) entry, which uses overlapping FVGs instead of range boundaries.",
    "Attempting to pre-identify the consolidation range before the manipulation reveals it.",
    "Not adjusting targets to aligned structural levels (e.g., opposite liquidity, FVGs), missing larger moves.",
    "Trading within the consolidation range instead of waiting for the breakout and retest.",
    "Entering without waiting for CISD or order block confirmation, leading to false retests.",
    "Confusing Box Setup with Inducement – Box Setup requires aggressive deviation and return, while Inducement is a false breakout followed by reversal.",
    "Using box boundaries incorrectly (e.g., mixing bodies and wicks) leading to wrong target calculations.",
    "Ignoring AMD phases, mistaking manipulation for distribution and missing the true entry."
  ],
